comments.body:
thanks [~sjones] for the quick reply. Sadly all the logs rolled over very quickly with 

{code}
WARN | javax.persistence.PersistenceException: org.hibernate.exception.GenericJDBCException: Cannot open connection
{code}

on both primary and secondary CLC so we cannot tell if there was a lot of logs writing beforehand. We will investigate the cloud and see if we see excessive logging.

[~kedwards] Can I get your thoughts on this:
Looking at the .hprof I am seeing 402MB out of a total 1000MB being held by org.postgresql.jdbc4.Jdbc4Connection,
this in turn holds a reference to com.eucalyptus.entities.Entities$CascadingTx$TxState.
In the logs I am seeing over 300,000 times : WARN [Entities:SystemHzTimer] [com.eucalyptus.entities.Entities$CascadingTx$TxState.begin(Entities.java):833] 
javax.persistence.PersistenceException : org.hibernate.exception.GenericJDBCException: Cannot open connection
Looking at the code I see that if the call to Entities.java line 833 fails in com.eucalyptus.entities.Entities$CascadingTx$TxState.begin
we just log the warning and re-throw the PersistenceException.  I think what we should be doing is cleaning up the transaction/session
i.e :
{code}
@@ -901,16 +901,17 @@ public class Entities {
        */
       @Override
       public void begin( ) {
         try {
           this.transaction.begin( );
         } catch ( final RuntimeException ex ) {
           LOG.warn( ex );
           Logs.extreme( ).warn( ex, ex );
+          doCleanup();
           throw ex;
         }
       }
{code}

Your thoughts Ken? I have no way to reproduce this in house.
